post_text:
Attention Parents and Guardians: On October 7th, your 2019-2020 meal application for Free/Reduced meals will expire and your child will be expected to pay full price for breakfast and lunch if eating in the school cafeteria. A meal application for the 2020-21 school year must be completed and approved in order to receive benefits after October 7th. You may complete an online application by clicking on the Child Nutrition link on the BISD website or you can request a paper application from the Child Nutrition Office located at 1301 Niebuhr St.

For more information visit the Brenham ISD Child Nutrition page: https://buff.ly/2AXCxLD

post_text: Due to current Covid-19 restrictions and for the safety of our patrons, ticket takers, and community, all Brenham ISD athletic tickets will be sold online. post_text: Part of what helps a student thrive is having a nutritious meal. Brenham ISD is proud to serve many children meals, and for some, this may be the only meal that they will have. This year our lunchrooms will continue to be the heart of the campus but with added safety measures to ensure a safe and healthy environment for students and staff. Sandra Baxter, Child Nutrition Director, gives us an insider look at the changes students can expect when coming to the lunchroom.

Friendly Reminder: Don't miss our 7/30/20 Thursday Briefing with Interim Superintendent, Huey Kinchen.

We want to thank our Brenham ISD families and community for the overwhelming support we are receiving as we prepare to start school on August 25.

In an effort to provide clear communication and stay responsive to the needs of our families, interim superintendent, Huey Kinchen will be discussing frequently asked questions along with important updates. Stay tuned to our Facebook page tonight at 7:30 p.m. and thank you for your support!

Brenham ISD wants to provide food and nutrition to our students even during this time while school is closed, so we‚Äôre announcing a new program that will deliver meals at your doorstep for free. This program is called Meals-to-You, and it is a partnership between our district, the U.S. Department of Agriculture, and Baylor University. Brenham ISD students who are already eligible for free or reduced-priced meals are invited to participate in the program.

When you sign up to get a Meals-to-You, every other week you‚Äôll get a Meals-to-You box delivered to your home for each child 1-18 in your household. Each box will include 10 breakfasts and 10 lunches/suppers‚Äîenough food for each kid for two weeks!

Find details here: https://www.brenhamisd.net/page/covid.meals

Brenham ISD students who are already eligible for free or reduced-priced meals are invited to participate in the program.

When you sign up to get a Meals-to-You, every other week you‚Äôll get a Meals-to-You box delivered to your home for each child 1-18 in your household. Each box will include 10 breakfasts and 10 lunches/suppers‚Äîenough food for each kid for two weeks!

Find details here: https://www.brenhamisd.net/page/covid.meals

In order to provide an emergency response for children ages 1-18 in Washington County, the Boys & Girls Club of Washington County will have 200 food boxes from the Brazos Valley Food Bank to distribute on Friday, May 1st from 11am to 1pm. The distribution will take place at the Boys & Girls Club of Washington County located at 1710 East Tom Green Street and will provide one box of shelf-ready groceries per family on a first-come, first-served basis.

A box of shelf-ready groceries and one bag of produce per family will be distributed. The Emergency Family food box program works to fill the weekend meal gap for youth by providing food to have over the weekend.

Date: Friday, May 1, 2020
Time: 11:00 am - 1:00pm or until supplies last
Location: Boys & Girls Club of Washington County, 1710 East Tom Green Street, Brenham, TX

You do not have to be a Club member to receive a box. However, you will be asked to provide some information.

To expedite the distribution process households are strongly encouraged to preregister. https://forms.gle/VRjcnmuMLfUxmLEV9

In order to provide an immediate response for children ages 1-18 in Washington County, the Boys & Girls Club of Washington County will have 200 food boxes from the Brazos Valley Food Bank to distribute on Friday, April 17 from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. The distribution will take place at the Boys & Girls Club of Washington County located at 1710 East Tom Green Street and will provide one box of shelf-ready groceries per family on a first-come, first-served basis. Children must be present in the vehicle to receive food boxes.

Because our local food pantries are supplied by the Brazos Valley Food Bank and can provide a long-term, sustainable solution, we also encourage families to seek additional aid from these established organizations. Families can visit forthecity.center for a list of all local food pantries involved in the Washington County COVID-19 response.

post_text:
Because a great number of our students rely on school district nutrition programs for food, Brenham ISD will provide a free drive-thru hot lunch and bagged breakfast for all students during the closure. Beginning on Monday, March 23, Brenham ISD will be adding two additional meal service sites. Meals may be picked up at the following locations:

Alton Elementary School
1210 S. Market St, Brenham, TX
11:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m.

Brenham High School
525 A.H. Ehrig Dr, Brenham, TX
11:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m.

Goodwill Missionary Baptist Church
9180 Texas Highway 105, Brenham, TX
11:30 a.m. to 12:30 p.m.

District staff will deliver food to the vehicle; families will not need to exit their vehicle to receive the meals. Food will be provided for all children between the ages of 1-18. Children must be present in the vehicle to receive the meal.

The district team is also working on a plan to meet the needs of our students and families who are without transportation or live in remote areas of our community.

The Washington-on-the-Brazos State Historical Park recently celebrated Texas Independence in a unique way. Students from 7th grade pre-AP Texas history classes at Brenham Junior High School were given the task of writing an essay on the topic: "A Texas Figure Who Inspires Me Most." Top essays were chosen by staff of the historical site and the student authors were hailed as Monument Scholars, participating in a ceremony on Feb. 29, 2020 to place a wreath on the monument at Independence Hall.

L to R: Faith Sartor, Samantha Robinson, Rylee Davis, Lillian Gonzales

On Wednesday, March 4, Brenham ISD will present the third annual Cub Talks Emerging Leaders Symposium, a student leadership opportunity for junior high and high school students. Cub Talks will take place from 9:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. in the Brenham High School auditorium.

This event will feature guest speakers presenting short talks to help students develop the confidence and leadership skills necessary for success in school and in life. The featured speaker for Cub Talks 2020 is Miss Texas 2019 Chandler Foreman!

Other Cub Talks special guest speakers include:
Kassie Jones, Bush School of Government and Public Service
Dr. Kozhi Makai, Kozhi Makai Worldwide
Mark Pennybacker, Washington County Census Complete Count Committee
Danny Ramsey, Brenham ISD Assistant Athletic Director

Although the Cub Talks event is targeted at our developing youth leaders, we invite any of our parents or community members to join us on Wednesday, March 4 from 9:00 a.m. to 12:00 p.m. in the Brenham High School auditorium.

Superintendent's Award, Addison Schramme
5th place Biomedical and Health Science, Abbey Cross
5th place Earth and Environmental Science, Addison Schramme
1st place Materials, Cullen Halfmann
3rd place Materials, Joshua Parker
3rd place Microbiology, Madison Moran
3rd place Plant Science (Senior Division), Emily Crawley
